We noticed that the film date and published date were stored in the POSIXct format which is not very informative.
To solve that problem we will extract a proper date and add new columns (features) representing the day, month and year of the date.

require(anytime)
require(data.table)

ted_talks$film_date = anydate(ted_talks$film_date)
ted_talks$film_day = weekdays(ted_talks$film_date,abbreviate = TRUE) #gives the day
ted_talks$film_month = month(ted_talks$film_date) #gives the month
ted_talks$film_year = year(ted_talks$film_date) #gives the year

ted_talks$published_date = anydate(ted_talks$published_date)
ted_talks$published_day = weekdays(ted_talks$published_date,abbreviate = TRUE) #gives the day
ted_talks$published_month = month(ted_talks$published_date) #gives the month
ted_talks$published_year = year(ted_talks$published_date) #gives the year

Plotting a histogram for all numeric columns

Secondly, we will use a very convenient function of ggplot to create histograms of each numeric variable.
This will help us to identify possible outliers and the distribution of data.

require(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = melt(ted_talks), mapping = aes(x = value)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) + facet_wrap(~variable, scales = 'free_x')

Cleaning numeric data

1.Finding outliers

We will analyze the summary and histograms we just produced.

We can first observe that some numeric columns have easily identifiable outliers. For example the num_speaker column has a value of 99999 which I can hardly imagine occuring. Similarly the languages column has a value of 999 which is definitely too much.

The film year, published_year, film_date, published_date columns have values from 1972 which is quite an extreme since the mean and median values are in the range of 2011 and 2012.

All other columns actually seem to have clean data without outliers.

2. Fixing outliers

Lets first see in more details the distribution of dates. Specifically we are fixing these columns film year, published_year, film_date, published_date:

hist(ted_talks$film_date,breaks=100, col="wheat",main="Distribution of the years when TED talks were filmed", xlab = "Film date")

Because they are quite rare (and dont make much sense) we will manually replace the date values that are before 1995 for published and filmed dates (for all 4 columns we mentioned) with the respective medians.

ted_talks$film_date[(ted_talks$film_date< "1995-01-01")] <- median(ted_talks$film_date, na.rm=TRUE)

ted_talks$published_date[(ted_talks$published_date< "1995-01-01")] <- median(ted_talks$published_date, na.rm=TRUE)

ted_talks$film_year[(ted_talks$film_year< 1995)] <- median(ted_talks$film_year, na.rm=TRUE)

ted_talks$published_year[(ted_talks$published_year< 1995)] <- median(ted_talks$published_year, na.rm=TRUE)

Lastly we will focus on the num_speaker and languages columns.

For num_speaker column we just have to remove the one outlier with 99999 speakers. I will replace all events with more than 10 speakers with the median of all values.
For languages we will do the same for values above 400.

ted_talks$num_speaker[(ted_talks$num_speaker > 10)] <- median(ted_talks$num_speaker, na.rm=TRUE)

ted_talks$languages[(ted_talks$languages > 400)] <- median(ted_talks$languages, na.rm=TRUE)

3. Finding NA values

Lets now see how many NA values we had in each column:

sapply(ted_talks, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))

It seems that num_speaker column is a bit problematic with regards to missing values.

4. Fixing NA values

We will fill in those values with the respective median value.

ted_talks$num_speaker[is.na(ted_talks$num_speaker)] <- median(ted_talks$num_speaker, na.rm=TRUE)

Cleaning character data

From the summary we can observe that it was not very informative for character columns name, event, film_day and published_day. To combat this we will explore them using a barplot.

barplot( table(ted_talks$published_day),col = "wheat", main="Number Of TED Talks published on a day in the week")

3 Associations between variables

Now we will now create a chart that shows a scatter plot between two numerical variables together with their correlation.
To perform this task we will use a very useful library called PerformanceAnalytics that plots two numerical variables on a scatter plot as well as calculate their correlation coefficient.
This provides us a very nice visual view of the variables along with a mathematical measure.

So on the chart we have: On top-right side of the chart we have the absolute value of the correlation (Pearson method) and number of stars based on p-value.
On bottom-left side of the chart we have the (bivariate) scatterplots along with a fitted line. 

library("PerformanceAnalytics")
suppressWarnings(chart.Correlation(ted_talks[sapply(ted_talks,is.numeric)] , method = "pearson", histogram = TRUE, pch = '+'))

First of all we have to take some of these results with a grain of salt as some numeric variables are not very telling. For example the published_month and film_month variables do not seem to be significantly correlated with any other column. They arent even correlated together.

Some expected relationships (correlations) we drew from these plots:
* the number of languages that a talk was translated into is negatively correlated with its duration
* the number of comments is closely correlated with the number of views. The coefficient of 0.53
* the published year and filmed year are the two most correlated variables (which makes a lot of sense)

Some unexpected relationships (correlations) we drew from these plots:
* there is a strange correlation between the year the TED talk was filmed/produced at and the length of its name meaning that newer talks have longer names (titles)
* talks that were published in more recent years have a larger number of comments
* the number of languages that a talk was translated into is slowly reducing with time
* the duration of a talk is negatively correlated with the year the talk was filmed/published meaning that newer talks are getting shorter

4 Relationship of variables with the number of views

How does the day in the week affect the number of views?

We are now also interested in how the number of views is affected by other variables.
To start off lets compare the number of views a TED talk video gets based on the day its published and filmed

library(gridExtra)
ggplot(ted_talks, aes(x=ted_talks$film_day, y=ted_talks$views))  + stat_summary(fun.y="mean", geom="bar")+ labs(y="Number of views", x = "Day in the week") + ggtitle("Mean num of views- filmed day") -> p1

ggplot(ted_talks, aes(x=ted_talks$published_day, y=ted_talks$views)) + stat_summary(fun.y="mean", geom="bar") + labs(y="Number of views", x = "Day in the week") + ggtitle("Mean num of views- published day") -> p2

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)

From this plot we can observe that videos published on weekends (Saturday, Sunday) receive fewer videos.
But taking into account the previous chart showing that on those days the frequency of publishing videos is very low we must take this fact with a grain of salt.

Which events provide the highest number of views?

Now we want to see how the event on which the talk was held has effect on the number of views.
To do that we first calculate the median number of views TED talks have for that event.
Then we filter events whose median number of views for all TED talks is two standard deviations higher than the average of the same metric for all events.
Lastly we plot those events on a barchart ordered by the median number of views a talk received on this event.

data_raw <- setNames( aggregate(ted_talks$views, list(ted_talks$event), median), c("event", "views"))
p <- data.table(data_raw)
p <- p[,ToKeep := (p$views-mean(p$views)) > 2 * sd(p$views)][ToKeep  == TRUE] 

ggplot(p,aes(x= reorder(p$event,-p$views),p$views))+geom_bar(stat ="identity") + labs(y="Median number of views", x = "Name of the event") + ggtitle("Median number of views per talk on this event")

We observe some events indeed have a much higher median number of views but their number is not that high.

Correlating the number of views with other variables

Now we will again plot the previous chart of scatter plot with correlation between different numerical variables but we will remove the uninformative columns to get a crisper picture.

suppressWarnings(chart.Correlation(subset(ted_talks[sapply(ted_talks,is.numeric)], select = -c(film_month,published_month,num_speaker) ), method = "pearson", histogram = TRUE, pch = '+'))

Conclusion

From the chart above and the analysis of how day in the week and the specific event affect the number of views, we observe that the events that affect the number of views a talk receives is the following (in order of relevance):
1. Number of comments left on the video of the talk (correlation of 0.53 ie. more comments lead to more views but this is not a causal relationship)
2. Number of languages the video was translated into (correlation of 0.32 ie. the more languages the video is translated into the more viewed it is)
3. Day on which the video was published (videos published on Saturday and Sunday have fewer views)
4. Specific event the talk was held on as some events hold a higher median number of views than other
5. If the name of the talk is very long it will receive fewer views
6. The year the talk was filmed or published and the duration of the video do not seem to be play a major role

Of course these are just our observations and a large number of these conclusions are just correlations that dont guarantee causation.
